<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-167-966  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 167 966.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Information Executive  Wntr 1990 v3 n1 p47(4).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Estimating project risk.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Roetzheim, William H.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Most data processing companies believe they can begin new softwaredevelopment projects without being sure that the technology existsto complete them, which is the reason why 15 percent of suchprojects fail to deliver any useful product.andP;  Project evaluationshould be done at every critical decision point, three of whichare typical in computer projects: proceeding from feasibility todesign, proceeding from design to development, and proceeding fromdevelopment to operation.andP;  The three steps involved in estimatinga project's risk are the likelihood of failure factor, theconsequence of failure factor and the combination of the twofactors to determine the overall project risk factor.andO;Mathematical models are provided for calculating the likelihood offailure factor, technical failure factor, cost failure factor,schedule failure factor and dependency failure factor.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Project ManagementRisk AnalysisMathematical ModelsSystem DevelopmentSoftware DesignProgram Development TechniquesProgramming ManagementEstimationTutorial.andO;Feature:   illustrationcharttable.andO;Caption:   Critical decision points. (chart)Calculating project risk. (chart)Consequence of failure factor guidelines. (table)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>